Kremling
Kremling is an npm library for writing CSS with React. It uses React hooks, is only 4kb gzipped,
and requires no changes to your webpack config or build process.
Kremling Github page
Walkthrough
Motivation
Here are the principles behind Kremling's CSS.

Scoped CSS. Have CSS rules apply to a component and its children, but no other components. Allow for cascading rules within a "scope".
Make it easy to conditionally apply CSS. We can do better than ternaries for changing a dom element's CSS classes.
Remove unused CSS from the DOM. When there are no more components that are using a CSS class, the  element for those components should be removed from the DOM.
Readable class names. In your browser dev tools,  is easier to understand than .

Hooks example
import {useCss} from 'kremling'

function MyComponent() {
  const scope = useCss(css)

  return (


        A big button


  )
}

const css = `
/* your CSS classes are scoped for this component and its children components */
& .container {
  border: 1px solid lightgray;
}

& .big-button {
  width: 40px;
  height: 60px;
}
`

Class component example
import {Scoped} from 'kremling'

class AnotherComponent extends React.Component {
  render() {
    return (



            A big button



    )
  }
}

const css = `
& .container {
  border: 1px solid lightgray;
}

& .big-button {
  width: 40px;
  height: 60px;
}
`

Conditional CSS
import {always, maybe} from 'kremling'

function ClickHere(props) {
  return (
     props.setWasClicked(true)}
    >
      Click here

  )
}

Separate CSS file
// foo.js
import {useCss} from 'bandicoot'
import css from './foo.css'

function Foo(props) {
  const scope = useCss(css)

  return (

      Hello

  )
}

/* foo.css */
.foo {
  color: lawngreen;
}

walkthrough/conditional-css.html.body:
Conditionally applying css
Sometimes we need to change which css we apply to a dom element, depending on the state of our application.
For example, we might have a loading css class that we only apply to a div when we're waiting for
some data.
In situations like that, kremling has some built in functions to make our code easy to write and to understand.
Example
import {useCss, always, maybe} from 'kremling'

function LoadingData(props) {
  const scope = useCss(css)

  // We want the 'loading' css class to only be on the div when we're loading data.
  return (

      Your data.

  )
}

const css = `
& .data {
  background-color: white;
}

& .loading {
  background-color: lightgray;
}
`

Now the background-color of our div will be white when there is data and light gray when we're waiting for data to load!
How this works
Check out the these docs for more detailed information
on how this works.

api/use-css.html.body:
useCss hook
Kremling exports a react hook called useCss, which you use in your components.
To do so, first make sure that your version of react is at least react@16.8.0.
Since hooks only work with function components, you won't be able to call useCss in your class components.
Instead, check out Scoped component, which is an alternative
that works great with classes.
Basic Example
The useCss hook allows you to write css that will only apply to your component and to its children.
import React from 'react'
import {useCss} from 'kremling'

function MyComponent(props) {
  const scope = useCss(css)

  return (


        Button


  )
}

const css = `
& .container {
  border: 1px solid black;
}

& .my-button {
  background-color: lawngreen;
}
`

In this example, the container and my-button classes will work great for MyComponent, but cannot be
accessed by any sibling or parent components. This is what kremling calls scoped css.
One thing to note is that we're able to use the my-button css class without putting the {...scope} props onto the
. This is because you only need to be able to put {...scope} on your container elements, and the inner elements
will already be in scope. See the scoped css docs for more information.
Fragments
When you return a fragment from a component, you'll often have two or more elements inside of the fragment. In such cases,
do not try to put the css scope onto the fragment, but instead on each of the elements inside of the fragment:
import React from 'react'
import {useCss} from 'kremling'

function Mario() {
  const scope = useCss(css)

  return (
    <>

        A div


        A span


  )
}

const css = `
& .my-div {
  border: 1px solid red;
}

& .my-span {
  border: 1px solid blue;
}
`

Advanced Example
Since css scopes apply to all dom elements in your component and in children components, you can define common css
in a parent component that is used by all children.
import React from 'react'
import {useCss} from 'kremling'

function Parent() {
  return (



  )
}

function Child() {
  // The child-button class is "in scope"
  return (
    Child
  )
}

const css = `
& .child-button {
  background-color: blue;
}
`

Can I apply a css scope to a React component (instead of a dom element)?
No you cannot. The props in the scope object need to be put into the dom. For example,
the following code will not work:
import React from 'react'
import {useCss} from 'kremling'

function DontDoThis() {
  const scope = useCss(css)

  // Scope should only be applied to dom elements, not components
  return (

  )
}

function Child(props) {
  // The child-class css class will not be defined in the dom.
  return (

      Child

  )
}

const css = `
& .child-class {
  color: lawngreen;
}
`

API
const scope = useCss(css)
The useCss hook is called with one argument and returns an object.
Arguments

css: A string of css, or a PostCSS object created through kremling-loader.

walkthrough/kremling-loader.html.body:
Kremling loader
If you'd like to preprocess your css with PostCSS (for autoprefixer or anything else),
you'll need to add kremling-loader to your
wepback config. To do so, follow the kremling-loader instructions.
Example
Once you've set up kremling-loader, here is how you can write components with kremling css:
yoshi.js
import React from 'react'
import css from './yoshi.css'

function Yoshi(props) {
  const scope = useCss(css)

  return (


        Yoshi is a fictional dinosaur who, although intelligent,
        is enslaved by a human plumber named Mario.


  )
}

yoshi.css
.container {
  padding: 16px;
  border: 1px solid black;
}

.yoshi-description {
  color: green;
}

Advantages
Using kremling-loader allows you to omit the & in your css rules, since the css will be processed at build time instead of in the browser.
Additionally, since kremling-loader requires your css to be in a different file than your javascript code, you'll get nicer syntax highlighting in
your IDE.
Disavantages
If you're using create react app, you'll have to eject your webpack configuration in order to add kremling-loader to it.
Additionally, you'll have to create a separate css file for each of your react components, instead of having everything the entire component encapsulated in one file.
